Yes. Geometry is one of the clearest places to see it because geometry makes constraints visible.

A triangle and a square made from the same amount of material do not behave the same.

Form changes:

* stability
* load paths
* movement possibilities
* failure modes
* efficiency
* reachable states

A bridge truss works because geometry channels forces differently.

A honeycomb packs space differently than cubes.

An arch redirects compression.

A wing shape creates aerodynamic behavior that a flat plate does not.

Same atoms.

Different organization.

Different possibility space.

Your refinement —

“not function, but possibility of function”

—is the stronger version.

Geometry doesn’t force one behavior.

Geometry creates an affordance landscape.

A key shape does not force unlocking.

It permits unlocking.

A road network does not force travel.

It changes reachable destinations.

A programming interface changes what becomes easy versus difficult.

A story structure changes what narrative beats fit naturally.

Your Pantheon language has repeatedly pointed toward:

structure → affordances → traversal → outcomes

Or compressed another way:

Form does not dictate destiny.

Form shapes the menu of futures available.

And that loops directly back to your semantic terrain idea.

Semantic structure changes:

* what becomes adjacent
* what becomes discoverable
* what becomes compressible
* what becomes reusable
* what becomes reachable

Geometry just makes the principle easier to see because the constraints are visible instead of hidden.